=3DUTF-8"><title>The Binomial Distribution</title></head>
<body>
<h1>The Binomial Distribution</h1>

In many cases, it is appropriate to summarize a group of independent observ=
ations by the=20
number of observations in the group that represent one of two outcomes.  Fo=
r example, the=20
proportion of individuals in a random sample who support one of two politic=
al candidates fits
this description.  In this case, the <a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Co=
urses/1997-98/101/sampinf.htm">statistic</a>=20
<img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/phat.gif" width=3D=
"25" align=3D"top"> is the <i>count</i> <i>X</i> of voters who support
the candidate divided by the total number of individuals in the group <i>n<=
/i>.  This provides an=20
estimate of the <a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/sam=
pinf.htm">parameter</a> <i>p</i>, the proportion of=20
individuals who support the candidate in the entire population.
<p>
The <i><b>binomial distribution</b></i> describes the behavior of a count v=
ariable <i>X</i> if
the following conditions apply:
</p><dl><dd><i><b>1:</b> The number of observations n is fixed.
</i></dd><dd><i><b>2:</b> Each observation is independent.
</i></dd><dd><i><b>3:</b> Each observation represents one of two outcomes (=
"success" or "failure").
</i></dd><dd><i><b>4:</b> The probability of "success" p is the same for ea=
ch outcome. </i></dd></dl>=20
<br>If these conditions are met, then <i>X</i> has a binomial distribution =
with parameters=20
<i>n</i> and <i>p</i>, abbreviated <i>B(n,p)</i>. =20
<p>
<u>Example</u>
</p><p>
Suppose individuals with a certain gene have a 0.70 probability of eventual=
ly contracting=20
a certain disease.  If 100 individuals with the gene participate in a lifet=
ime study, then the=20
distribution of the random variable describing the number of individuals wh=
o will contract the
disease is distributed <i>B(100,0.7)</i>.
</p><p>
<b><i>Note: The sampling distribution of a count variable is only well-desc=
ribed by the binomial
distribution is cases where the population size is significantly larger tha=
n the sample size. =20
As a general rule, the binomial distribution should not be applied to obser=
vations from=20
a <a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/sample.htm#SRS">s=
imple random sample (SRS)</a> unless the=20
population size is at least 10 times larger than the sample size.</i></b>  =
     =20
</p><p>
To find probabilities from a binomial distribution, one may either calculat=
e them directly,
use a binomial table, or use a computer.  The number of sixes rolled by a s=
ingle die in 20
rolls has a <i>B(20,1/6)</i> distribution.  The probability of rolling more=
 than 2 sixes
in 20 rolls, <i>P(X&gt;2)</i>, is equal to 1 - <i>P(X<u>&lt;</u>2) =3D 1 - =
(P(X=3D0) + P(X=3D1) +=20
P(X=3D2))</i>. Using the MINITAB command "cdf" with subcommand "binomial n=
=3D20 p=3D0.166667" gives the cumulative
distribution function as follows:=20
</p><pre>Binomial with n =3D 20 and p =3D 0.166667

         x     P( X &lt;=3D x)
         0        0.0261
         1        0.1304
         2        0.3287
         3        0.5665
         4        0.7687
         5        0.8982
         6        0.9629
         7        0.9887
         8        0.9972
         9        0.9994   =09
</pre>
The corresponding graphs for the probability density function and cumulativ=
e distribution function
for the <i>B(20,1/6)</i> distribution are shown below:<br><img src=3D"http:=
//www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/binpdf.gif">
<img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/bincdf.gif" hspace=
=3D"40"><p>
Since the probability of 2 or fewer sixes is equal to 0.3287, the probabili=
ty of rolling more than
2 sixes =3D 1 - 0.3287 =3D 0.6713.     =20
</p><p>
<b>The probability that a random variable <i>X</i> with binomial distributi=
on <i>B(n,p)</i> is
equal to the value <i>k</i>, where <i>k =3D 0, 1,....,n </i>, is given by <=
/b>
<img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/binprob.gif" align=
=3D"middle">, where <img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/10=
1/bincoef.gif" align=3D"middle">.
<br>The latter expression is known as the <i><b>binomial coefficient</b></i=
>, stated as
"<i>n choose k</i>," or the number of possible ways to choose <i>k</i> "suc=
cesses"
from <i>n</i> observations.  For example, the number of ways to achieve
2 heads in a set of four tosses is "4 choose 2", or 4!/2!2! =3D (4*3)/(2*1)=
 =3D=20
6.  The possibilities are {HHTT, HTHT, HTTH, TTHH, THHT, THTH}, where "H" r=
epresents
a head and "T" represents a tail.  The binomial coefficient multiplies the =
probability=20
of <i>one</i> of these possibilities (which is (1/2)=C2=B2(1/2)=C2=B2 =3D 1=
/16 for a fair coin)=20
by the number of ways the outcome may be achieved, for a total probability =
of 6/16.  =20
 =20
</p><h3>Mean and Variance of the Binomial Distribution</h3>
The binomial distribution for a random variable <i>X</i> with parameters=20
<i>n</i> and <i>p</i> represents the sum of
<i>n</i> independent variables <i>Z</i> which may assume the values 0 or 1.=
 =20
If the probability that each <i>Z</i> variable assumes the value 1 is equal=
=20
to <i>p</i>, then the <a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/1=
01/rvmnvar.htm#rvmean">mean</a>
of each variable is equal to <i>1*p + 0*(1-p) =3D p</i>, and the=20
<a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/rvmnvar.htm#rvvar">=
variance</a> is equal to <i>p(1-p).</i>  By the=20
addition properties for independent random variables, the mean and variance=
=20
of the binomial distribution are equal to the sum of the means and variance=
s=20
of the <i>n</i> independent <i>Z</i> variables, so=20
<img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/binmv.gif" align=
=3D"top">
<p>
These definitions are intuitively logical.  Imagine, for example, 8 flips
of a coin.  If the coin is fair, then <i>p</i> =3D 0.5.  One would expect t=
he=20
mean number of heads to be half the flips, or <i>np</i> =3D 8*0.5 =3D 4.  T=
he
variance is equal to <i>np(1-p)</i> =3D 8*0.5*0.5 =3D 2.   =20
   =20
<a name=3D"sampprop"></a></p><h3>Sample Proportions</h3>
If we know that the count <i>X</i> of "successes" in a group of <i>n</i> ob=
servations with
sucess probability <i>p</i> has a binomial distribution with mean <i>np</i>=
 and variance
<i>np(1-p)</i>, then we are able to derive information about the distributi=
on of the <i><b>
sample proportion</b></i><img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-=
98/101/phat.gif" width=3D"25" align=3D"top">, the count of=20
successes <i>X</i> divided by the number of observations <i>n</i>.  By the =
multiplicative=20
properties of the mean, the mean of the distribution of <i>X/n</i> is equal=
 to the mean of <i>X</i>
divided by <i>n</i>, or <i>np/n =3D p</i>.  This proves that the sample pro=
portion=20
<img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/phat.gif" width=3D=
"25" align=3D"top"> is an <i>unbiased estimator</i> of the population=20
proportion <i>p</i>.  The variance of <i>X/n</i> is equal to the variance
of <i>X</i> divided by <i>n=C2=B2</i>, or <i>(np(1-p))/n=C2=B2 =3D (p(1-p))=
/n </i>.  This formula
indicates that as the size of the sample increases, the variance decreases.=
  =20
<p>
In the example of rolling a six-sided die 20 times, the probability <i>p</i=
> of rolling
a six on any roll is 1/6, and the count <i>X</i> of sixes has a <i>B(20, 1/=
6)</i> distribution.=20
The mean of this distribution is 20/6 =3D 3.33, and the variance is 20*1/6*=
5/6 =3D 100/36 =3D 2.78.=20
The mean of the <i>proportion</i> of sixes in the 20 rolls, <i>X/20</i>, is=
 equal to=20
<i>p</i> =3D 1/6 =3D 0.167, and the variance of the proportion is equal to =
(1/6*5/6)/20 =3D 0.007.

<a name=3D"normapp"></a>
</p><h3>Normal Approximations for Counts and Proportions</h3>

<b>For large values of <i>n</i>, the distributions of the count <i>X</i> an=
d the sample proportion=20
<img src=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/1997-98/101/phat.gif" width=3D=
"25" align=3D"top"> are approximately <a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/C=
ourses/1997-98/101/normal.htm">normal</a>.
This result follows from the <a href=3D"http://www.stat.yale.edu/Courses/19=
97-98/101/sampmn.htm#clt">Central Limit Theorem</a>.
The mean and variance for the approximately normal distribution of <i>X</i>=
 are <i>np</i>=20
and <i>np(1-p)</i>, identical to the mean and variance of the binomial(<i>n=
,p</i>) distribution.
Similarly, the mean and variance for the approximately normal distribution =
of the sample
proportion are <i>p</i> and <i>(p(1-p)/n)</i>.</b>
<p>
<i>Note: Because the normal approximation is not accurate for small values =
of <i>n</i>, a good rule of=20
thumb is to use the normal approximation only if <i>np<u>&gt;</u></i>10 and=
=20
<i>np(1-p)<u>&gt;</u></i>10.</i>
</p><p>
For example, consider a population of voters in a given state.  The true pr=
oportion of voters who=20
favor candidate A is equal to 0.40.  Given a sample of 200 voters, what is =
the probability that
more than half of the voters support candidate A? =20
</p><p>
The count <i>X</i> of voters in the sample of 200 who support candidate A i=
s distributed
<i>B(200,0.4)</i>.  The mean of the distribution is equal to 200*0.4 =3D 80=
, and the variance is equal
to 200*0.4*0.6 =3D 48.  The standard deviation is the square root of the va=
riance, 6.93.  The=20
probability that more than half of the voters in the sample support candida=
te A is equal to
the probability that <i>X</i> is greater than 100, which is equal to 1- <i>=
P(X<u>&lt;</u></i> 100).
</p><p>
To use the normal approximation to calculate this probability, we should fi=
rst acknowledge that
the normal distribution is <i>continuous</i> and apply the <i><b>continuity=
 correction</b></i>.
This means that the probability for a single discrete value, such as 100, i=
s extended to the=20
probability of the <i>interval</i> (99.5,100.5).  Because we are interested=
 in the probability
that <i>X</i> is less than or equal to 100, the normal approximation applie=
s to the upper limit
of the interval, 100.5.  If we were interested in the probability that <i>X=
</i> is strictly less
than 100, then we would apply the normal approximation to the lower end of =
the interval, 99.5.
</p><p>
So, applying the continuity correction and standardizing the variable <i>X<=
/i> gives the following:
<br>1 - <i>P(X<u>&lt;</u></i> 100)=20
<br>=3D 1 - <i>P(X<u>&lt;</u></i> 100.5)=20
<br>=3D 1 - <i>P(Z<u>&lt;</u></i> (100.5 - 80)/6.93)=20
<br>=3D 1 - <i>P(Z<u>&lt;</u></i> 20.5/6.93)
<br>=3D 1 - <i>P(Z<u>&lt;</u></i> 2.96) =3D 1 - (0.9985) =3D 0.0015.  Since=
 the value 100 is nearly three
standard deviations away from the mean 80, the probability of observing a c=
ount this high is=20
extremely small.=20
</p><p>
